{"entries":[{"caption":"The probability of at least one false positive rises steeply as you conduct more tests. At 20 tests, there’s a 64% chance of at least one spurious ‘significant’ finding.","key":"fig-multiple-testing","order":{"number":12,"section":[9,10,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Factors that determine statistical power","key":"tbl-power-determinants","order":{"number":5,"section":[9,7,6,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Three different effect sizes. Note how overlap between the distributions decreases as effect size increases. All three could have p < 0.05 with adequate sample size.","key":"fig-effect-sizes","order":{"number":11,"section":[9,9,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Four scenarios illustrating the distinction between statistical and clinical significance","key":"tbl-clinical-examples","order":{"number":6,"section":[9,8,2,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"The fundamental trade-off: moving the critical value left decreases β (fewer misses) but increases α (more false alarms), and vice versa.","key":"fig-alpha-beta-tradeoff","order":{"number":9,"section":[9,7,7,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"The p-value is the red shaded area — the probability of getting a result this extreme (or more) if H₀ were true.","key":"fig-pvalue","order":{"number":7,"section":[9,6,2,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"The logical flow of statistical inference: CLT enables → CIs and hypothesis tests → interpreted through effect size and clinical significance.","key":"fig-concept-flow","order":{"number":14,"section":[9,12,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Confidence intervals tell you everything a p-value does — plus the magnitude and precision of the effect. Studies D and E both have p > 0.05, but D suggests a large effect with wide uncertainty (need more data) while E shows a precisely estimated null effect (truly no effect).","key":"fig-ci-forest","order":{"number":13,"section":[9,11,1,0,0,0,0]}},{"caption":"Two-tailed test splits α across both tails (more conservative); one-tailed test puts all α in one tail (more power but riskier)."